Garlic, Tomatoes, and EVOO Bucatini

This recipe is my latest obsession, helping me cope with FOMO from not traveling to Italy this summer! I've been making it once a week for over a month, and I can’t get enough of it. The truth is, I love making recipes with garlic, tomatoes, and extra virgin olive oil. Just two minutes into the cooking process, and the house immediately smells like a great Italian restaurant. The combination of tomatoes and fresh pistachio pesto is hard to beat, and together they create the perfect bite!

Check out the full recipe on my website!

FOMO is reeeaaal!

Most of my clients come to me and want to visit the whole Norway in 10 days… well, spoiler alert: it’s not possible. 

I know that when we travel to a different country we want to make the best out of it but at some point, it just becomes potential disappointment and something that will not be enjoyable. 

Stop trying to tick boxes and start enjoying the journey, the little things, the surprises… make time to take detours! This will create long lasting memories

Sentís que te estás perdiendo algo importante cuando ves las redes sociales? 
Eso se llama FOMO.

EI FOMO (Fear of Missing Out) es esa ansiedad de creer que otros están viviendo algo mejor, más divertido o más emocionante que vos.

Cómo se manifiesta?

• Revisás constantemente las redes para "no perderte nada".

• Te cuesta disfrutar el momento porque pensás en lo que no estás haciendo.

• Comparás tu vida con la de otros, sintiéndote insuficiente. Revisás constantemente las redes para "no perderte nada".

• Te cuesta disfrutar el momento porque pensás en lo que no estás haciendo.

• Comparás tu vida con la de otros, sintiéndote insuficiente.

✨ Sabías que el FOMO es una ilusión? Las redes muestran solo lo más destacado de la vida de los demás, no su realidad completa.

✅Tips para gestionarlo:
1️⃣Limita el tiempo en redes sociales.
2️⃣Practicá gratitud por lo que tenés enel presente.
3️⃣Enfocate en tus propios logros y metas.

 Te sentís identificado con el

A few more things I do + tips ✨ AD

• I don’t put all of my passport photo copies and debit/credit cards in the same place. They get spread out between my backpack, wallet, or other bags. 

• I do a quick search to see if there are any specific cultural norms or ways to dress I should be aware of. For example, in specific areas of Indonesia you ended to have your shoulders covered so I bought a short sleeve t shirt before I arrived. 

• If the main language is not english, I write down the basic words in the other language “hello”, “thank you”, “excuse me”, etc. 

@Airalo tips + how I use it 

You can download the app with the  in my bio & use code KAYLI3 for $3 off your first eSIM with Airalo :) 

• I use Airalo for data throughout different countries, so for using WhatsApp, social media, and various other phone apps. 

• I prefer to use an eSIM over a physical sim due to the convenience and for the fact that I don’t have to take my original sim card out. (I almost lost it once and would not want to deal with that)

• For my upcoming trip to Portugal I already know I’ll have data when I land! It just makes my life a bit easier in not having to search for sim cards once I get to the new country. 

• I go to the Airalo app, pick the country/region that I’m headed to (I’ve done regional eSIMs for places like Europe or SE Asia). I typically do 10GB per week(ish), depends on how much work I know I’ll be having to do or how easily accessible wifi is. 

• I activate the eSIM, but don’t “turn on the line” until I land in the new country. This way I can use my regular data in the states until I fly over to my destination.

I’m still choosing the bear though ⬇️ Grand Tetons NP  Baby bear was a bit to close for comfort and mama bear was no where is sight! I definitely kept my distance (about 10 feet)  ⛰️Honestly I was so stoked and shocked at the same time! It’s not everyday you get to see a baby bear that close, but that’s probably the last time I want to see a baby bear that close! All I know is I turned a corner and there it was! I was coming back down from a hike already paranoid because I was one of the only people on this trail, alone, with bear spray in hand because I know this trail was very known for having bears on it, little did I know I was going to come this close to one.  ‍❄️The thing that freaked me out the most was mama bear was no where to be seen! Was she behind me ready to attack? Was she a few feet ahead around the the switchback. I don’t think I’ve ever been so terrified and anxious on a hike in my life.  On the way down I did spot two more bears (1 black and 1 grizzly) from a much safer distance but I was sooo on edge!  Moral of the story! BRING THE BEAR SPRAY and stay alert!
